AU  - Smith, Gregor W.
Y1  - 2023/11/01
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2023/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12649
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1595
EP  - 1614
VL  - 64
IS  - 4
KW  - Inflation, price revolutions, stochastic volatility, time-varying parameters
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12649
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Historians have suggested that there were waves of inflation or price revolutions in the United Kingdom (and earlier England) in the 13th, 16th, and 18th centuries, prior to the ongoing inflation since 1935. We study retail price inflation since 1251 and model its dynamics. The model is an AR(n) but allows for gradually evolving or drifting parameters and stochastic volatility. The long-horizon forecasts suggest only one inflation wave, that of the 20th century. We also use the model to measure inflation predictability and price-level instability from the beginning of the sample and to provide measures of real interest rates since 1695.
ER  - 

